From 0cbaf29b9b337231c6c786852d96d9ecc6d9038d Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Vivian Wang <wangruikang@iscas.ac.cn>
Date: Tue, 7 Jul 2026 09:35:50 +0800
Subject: [RUYI PATCH] RUYI: HACK: riscv: entry: nmi_exit() before die()

Breakpoint exceptions are handled in_nmi() since they could be kernel
breakpoints. As such, nmi_exit() before die() to give the kernel a
chance to recover instead of having make_task_dead() generate a
full-machine panic.

This is similar to how some exceptions are handled in powerpc.

This is a bit of a hack. A better solution was being discussed [1] but
no concrete conclusion has been arrived to yet.

Link: https://lore.kernel.org/linux-riscv/20230702025708.784106-1-guoren@kernel.org/ # [1]
Signed-off-by: Vivian Wang <wangruikang@iscas.ac.cn>
Signed-off-by: Han Gao <gaohan@iscas.ac.cn>
---
 arch/riscv/kernel/traps.c | 7 +++++--
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/arch/riscv/kernel/traps.c b/arch/riscv/kernel/traps.c
index 47afea4ff1a8..65172f072f37 100644
--- a/arch/riscv/kernel/traps.c
+++ b/arch/riscv/kernel/traps.c
@@ -298,10 +298,13 @@ void handle_break(struct pt_regs *regs)
 		return;
 #endif
 	else if (report_bug(regs->epc, regs) == BUG_TRAP_TYPE_WARN ||
-		 handle_cfi_failure(regs) == BUG_TRAP_TYPE_WARN)
+		 handle_cfi_failure(regs) == BUG_TRAP_TYPE_WARN) {
 		regs->epc += get_break_insn_length(regs->epc);
-	else
+	} else {
+		/* Avoid a panic, since we're in_nmi(). */
+		nmi_exit();
 		die(regs, "Kernel BUG");
+	}
 }
 
 asmlinkage __visible __trap_section void do_trap_break(struct pt_regs *regs)
-- 
2.53.0

